align="left">Notes:<br><br></div><ul><li><b>Bold* </b>items with asterisk represent attributes that are required <br></li><li><i>Italic </i>items references a vocabulary item (i.e foreign key to the Vocabulary_Table) <br></li><li><u>Underlined</u> items references an item in another table (i.e. foreign key to the URI of the referenced table).</li><li>Variables are data collected throughout the study.<br></li><li>Biological Material, Environment, Experimental Factor and Observed variables are sub-classes of variables that provide additional information on how they are collected/used.</li><li>Environment variables are variables that are designed to be constant. A set-point with a corresponding unit should be provided for environment variables.</li><li>Observed variables are measured traits. Users should provide a reference to the method(s) used to derive this variable, and an appropriate unit. (Dependent variables in statistics)<br></li><li>Experimental Factor are independent variables in statistics terminology.</li><li>Observation Units can be the plant container (plot, sub-plot, crop, pot), or the plant itself.</li><li>Observation Units can be described hierarchically, using the parent attribute (-i.e. a plant contained in a pot contained in a plot)</li><li>Observation Units' FACTOR_SETTINGS describes the combination of experimental factors applied to the unit. For example, a plant treated with mycorrhizal with a Zinc level of 40 should be encoded similar to this: {"mycorrhizal": True, "zinc": 40}.<br></li><li>For the Facility_Table, the attribute VARIABLE_GROUP should reference a list of Environment variables that are monitored throughout the study. <br></li><li>The vocabulary table contains terms that reference an established ontology, or is a local definition for terms that have no external references. <br></li></ul>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="840" y="1039.6200000000001" width="530" height="397.79" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

ul.li: Bold* items with asterisk represent attributes that are required
Italic items references a vocabulary item (i.e foreign key to the Vocabulary_Table)
Underlined items references an item in another table (i.e. foreign key to the URI of the referenced table).
Variables are data collected throughout the study.
Biological Material, Environment, Experimental Factor and Observed variables are sub-classes of variables that provide additional information on how they are collected/used.
Environment variables are variables that are designed to be constant. A set-point with a corresponding unit should be provided for environment variables.
Observed variables are measured traits. Users should provide a reference to the method(s) used to derive this variable, and an appropriate unit. (Dependent variables in statistics)
Experimental Factor are independent variables in statistics terminology.
Observation Units can be the plant container (plot, sub-plot, crop, pot), or the plant itself.
Observation Units can be described hierarchically, using the parent attribute (-i.e. a plant contained in a pot contained in a plot)

Observation Units' FACTOR_SETTINGS describes the combination of experimental factors applied to the unit. For example, a plant treated with mycorrhizal with a Zinc level of 40 should be encoded similar to this: {"mycorrhizal": True, "zinc": 40}.
For the Facility_Table, the attribute VARIABLE_GROUP should reference a list of Environment variables that are monitored throughout the study.
The vocabulary table contains terms that reference an established ontology, or is a local definition for terms that have no external references.
